      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are correct that the act of defining an \"in-group\" inherently involves an \"out-group,\" which is a structural feature of any national identity. However, the difference lies in whether that boundary is drawn based on shared political values and laws, or on immutable characteristics like race or religion. Civic nationalism, which prioritizes shared political ideals, is fundamentally different from ethnic nationalism, which is inherently exclusionary and dangerous.",
